A10. Discover Privacy Technique Used Offline

For this activity, I explored a privacy technique implemented on my Windows device: device encryption.
Device encryption is a feature that encrypts the entire storage drive, protecting the information on the device from being accessed by unauthorized users or other devices. 
Only the user account associated with the device has the key required to decrypt the data, ensuring that sensitive information remains secure even if the device is lost or stolen.

How to Enable Device Encryption
1. Open Settings > Privacy & Security > Device Encryption.
2. Toggle the option to turn encryption on or off.

How to Verify Encryption Status

You can confirm whether device encryption is active by using the Command Prompt:

manage-bde -status

Before enabling encryption, the tool will display that protection is off.
After enabling encryption, it will indicate that protection is on, confirming that the device is encrypted.

This Demonstrates Privacy because:
Encryption ensures that only authorized users can access the device’s data.
Even if the storage drive is removed, the data cannot be read without the decryption key.
This is a real-world example of securing information without relying on internet services.
